## 1. Why this happened: the bubble anatomy

Howard Marks identifies eight recurring features of every investment bubble. Direct lending followed all eight with near-textbook precision.

**The essential element is newness.** When something is new, its proponents can stimulate interest by touting its merits and its flaws have yet to come to light. This is the necessary condition for a bubble. Direct lending was genuinely new — a form of credit that had never been tested through a full cycle when the bulk of capital flooded in from 2015 to 2022.

**There is usually a grain of truth.** The core thesis for lending to PE-backed software companies was real: recurring subscription revenues, low capital intensity, sticky customers, and the scarcity of bank capital post-GFC. The problem was not that the thesis was invented — it was that it was extrapolated far beyond the conditions under which it was valid.

**Early investors were rewarded.** The first direct lenders in 2010–2016 commanded strong terms, high yields, robust covenants, and chose from a genuine scarcity of available capital. Their returns validated the thesis. This set the trap for everyone who came after.

**Success made outsiders envious.** As Marks quotes Charles Kindleberger: "There is nothing so disturbing to one's well-being and judgment as to see a friend get rich." Institutional allocators who missed the early returns rushed to participate. This is the mechanism that converts a valid investment into an overcrowded one.

**The inflaming of hope.** Possibility was confused with probability and then became certainty. Yields of 9–11%, Sharpe ratios above 1.0, apparent low volatility — all of it was real, but what most investors failed to ask was whether those results would persist at the terms and prices available in 2021.

**The critical question was not asked.** "What price is safe to pay?" At the peak of the cycle, investors in 2021-vintage deals were lending at 8× leverage to ARR-model software companies at near-zero rates, effectively lending against a business model that had never been tested. Nobody asked whether those terms were safe, because nobody had to — the deals had always worked.

**Latecomers lowered standards.** The arrival of hundreds of new direct lending managers and several trillion dollars of incremental capital caused lenders to compete by accepting lower yields, narrower spreads, and reduced structural protections. The most important adage in investing, in Marks's formulation: "What the wise man does in the beginning, the fool does in the end." Or in Buffett's version: first the innovator, then the imitator, then the idiot.

**Flaws come to light.** The flaws overlooked during the good times — opacity, illiquidity, structurally low secondary market depth, originator incentives misaligned with portfolio quality, and the untested resilience of SaaS revenues — are now coming to light simultaneously.

This is not a novel story. It is the eternal recurrence of a pattern Marks has observed across high yield bonds in the 1980s, subprime mortgages in the 2000s, and direct lending today.

