## 3. The structural problems — what went wrong and why

Both Sona and Marks identify the same set of structural problems from different analytical angles. Together they provide a more complete picture than either alone.

**The originate-not-manage culture (Sona)**

The private credit industry was designed to originate. Its fee structures, staffing models, GP incentives, and fundraising narratives are all oriented around deployment. The implicit assumption embedded in the business model is that the most important decisions are made at origination and that monitoring can be largely mechanical thereafter. Sona argues this assumption is wrong.

As a result, many private credit portfolios were not constructed — they emerged as the accumulation of individual deployments. A genuine portfolio management culture requires continuous reassessment: whether the thesis on which an investment was underwritten remains valid, whether the competitive position of the borrower has changed, whether covenant levels still reflect the underlying risk, and crucially, the willingness and ability to walk away from an investment when circumstances call for it.

The concentration evidence supports the critique: why would a well-managed portfolio manager tolerate 40–50% exposure to software that was already showing signs of AI-driven competitive pressure? The answer lies in incentive structures. Managers who deployed capital most aggressively were rewarded with the highest fees and the largest subsequent fundraises.

**The lender willingness problem (Marks)**

Marks frames this differently but arrives at the same conclusion. The composition of the credit market is determined by lenders' willingness to supply capital, not by borrowers' needs. When hundreds of new direct lending managers entered the market with $2T of capital to deploy, the mathematics of competition required them to lower their standards. The benign economic environment that generally prevailed for 17 years post-GFC made direct loans successful despite weakening underwriting standards, allowing those trends to become more pronounced.

The manager incentive dilemma is real and Marks acknowledges it with unusual candour: join in when feverish investors are lowering their standards in order to put money to work, or sit on the sidelines and not invest, watching as other managers pile up AUM while clients potentially close their accounts in the interminable period before discipline finally pays off. This is not a criticism of individual managers but an observation about the structural incentive. The market rewards acceleration during the boom and punishes restraint.

**The convexity problem (Sona)**

Credit investing is inherently asymmetric in a way equity investing is not. The worst outcome is a total loss. Unlike equities, the best outcome is par — investors get their money back plus coupon income. There is no participation in the upside. In software specifically, private credit lenders accepted the downside risk of disruption while having no exposure to the equity upside if AI augmentation made software companies more valuable. The companies that were the most attractive private credit borrowers — high-leverage, ARR-model SaaS — are also the most exposed to AI disruption risk. The asymmetry is at its most extreme exactly where the concentration is highest.

**The 60% asset-light problem (Sona)**

Software at 26% of BDC portfolios is the acute risk, but Sona widens the aperture materially. Approximately 60% of BDC portfolios consist of asset-light businesses broadly defined — software, financial services, business process outsourcing, and any company whose competitive advantage rests primarily on human capital rather than hard assets. The comparative figures: €-HY at 16%, $-HY at 25%, €-BSL at 40%, $-BSL at 46%, BDCs at 58%. The AI disruption thesis is not a software story. It is an asset-light story, and asset-light is the majority of the BDC universe.

**The duration trap (Sona)**

The original investment thesis was built on a liquidity premium: investors accepted illiquidity in exchange for higher returns on the assumption that capital would be returned over a defined fund life. The reality has been different. Less than 1% of private credit AUM trades annually in the secondary market. Bain's 2026 Global Private Equity Report documents the PE side of this: buyout distributions as a percentage of NAV held at 14% for four consecutive years — the lowest since the GFC — with 32,000 unsold companies worth $3.8T sitting on GP books. Average holding periods at exit have extended to seven years from a historical five to six.

The duration trap interacts with AI disruption in a specific way. A private credit investor exposed to a deteriorating software company has almost no exit routes. They watch NAV drift further from economic reality while hoping a restructuring preserves some value.

