## 4. The data that proves it

These are not theoretical concerns. They have specific public evidence.

**The shadow default rate**

Lincoln International monitors 7,000 company valuations across 225+ asset managers globally. Their data is the most granular public read on private credit stress. The officially reported default rate remains around 3.4%. But Lincoln's shadow default rate — the percentage of companies using PIK that was inserted mid-deal rather than agreed at origination — has more than doubled from 2.5% of all deals in Q4 2021 to 6.4% in Q4 2025. PIK usage overall has risen to 11% of all deals, up from 7% in 2021, and 58% of current PIK deals had no PIK provision at origination. A mid-deal PIK insertion is a de facto admission that the borrower cannot service cash interest — which is a shadow default in economic substance even if not in legal form.

The structural implication: the 6.4% shadow default rate and the 3.4% reported rate are not measuring the same thing. The gap is where the real risk sits.

Additional Lincoln data corroborates the stress. The average LTV for companies with bad PIK was 45% at inception compared to 83% today — a clear sign of borrower balance sheet deterioration. In 2025, Lincoln observed lenders with $21B of pre-takeover principal gaining control of businesses — more than the total from 2019 through 2024 combined.

**The 2021 vintage concentration**

Goldman Sachs Asset Management built a proprietary database of European credit events (insolvencies and debt-for-equity swaps in direct lending) since 2017. Their finding: 2021-vintage deals have seen the steepest trajectory in the number of credit events experienced in the first three years after origination. The 2017–2018 vintage has the highest absolute count (it had to survive COVID, Ukraine, and rate rises), but the 2021 vintage is accelerating fastest. This vintage is particularly vulnerable because loans were structured for a near-zero rate environment and the borrowers had not yet grown EBITDA enough to offset the 400bp rate rise before their ICR came under pressure.

**The repeat default problem**

Fitch estimates that 30% of defaults recorded in European bond and loan markets in 2025 were repeat defaults — companies defaulting for a second time within two years of their initial default. That is up from 15% in 2024 and 13% in 2023. Repeat defaulters accounted for 32% of European HY defaults in 2025, with the average interval between the first and second default at eight months for HY and eleven months for leveraged loans. Fitch's interpretation: LMEs can "buy time but often leave balance sheets stretched." The restructuring frequently removes too little debt to restore genuine solvency, setting up a second event. At the start of 2026, 43% of CCC/C issuers in Europe were previous defaulters, up from 16% at the start of 2020.

This is the strongest available public evidence that the recovery rate assumption is more fragile than the MS central case implies. A bilateral LME that leaves 8× leverage on a SaaS company that is simultaneously facing AI disruption does not produce recovery — it produces a second default 8–11 months later.

**The PE distribution drought**

Bain's 2026 Global PE Report documents distributions as a percentage of NAV at 14% for four consecutive years — the lowest since 2008–09. The PE industry holds 32,000 unsold companies worth $3.8T with average holding periods of seven years. Marks adds the return data: MSCI estimates US PE funds saw annualised returns of 5.8% between 2022 and Q3 2025 versus 11.6% for the S&P 500. This matters for private credit because PE exits are the primary mechanism through which portfolio company debt gets repaid. If companies cannot be sold, maturities cannot be repaid through asset monetisation, forcing borrowers toward refinancing or restructuring at exactly the moment when private credit supply is contracting.

