## 5. The three case studies: First Brands, Tricolor, MFS

These three failures are not peripheral. They are illustrative of a structural weakness in how private credit and asset-based finance were underwritten during the expansion phase.

**First Brands Group (September 2025)**

First Brands entered 2025 carrying more than $10B in total debt and roughly $900M in annual interest obligations, the legacy of an aggressive roll-up strategy in aftermarket auto parts. When tariff headwinds compressed operating cash flow, the capital structure unravelled. Beneath the liquidity crisis lay something structural: approximately $2.3B in receivables had allegedly been diverted through commingling and overlapping facilities, with a Department of Justice inquiry focused on duplicate pledging and the accuracy of borrowing-base certificates. Lenders owned receivables on paper but did not control the incoming cash because retailers were remitting payments into accounts controlled by the company rather than into DACA-governed accounts.

**Tricolor Holdings (September 2025)**

Tricolor operated as a vertically integrated used-car dealer and subprime auto lender. The vulnerability was the fragmentation of state-level vehicle title infrastructure. Tricolor pledged the same consumer auto-loan portfolios to multiple financing partners while maintaining internal ledgers that could not be reconciled across facilities — creating a collateral position that existed in documentation but not in practice. The company ultimately filed directly for Chapter 7, bypassing reorganisation.

**Market Financial Solutions (February 2026)**

MFS built a £2.4B loan book in specialist UK property finance over nearly two decades, receiving a clean audit as recently as March 2025. The trigger: across loans totalling £1.2B, only £230M of verified collateral could be identified. The mechanism was double-pledging — the same properties were used to secure multiple separate loans from different lenders, each of whom believed they held exclusive security. MFS operated ten warehouse facilities simultaneously, with each lender managing a purely bilateral relationship with MFS as servicer and no visibility across the wider structure. No independent party monitored aggregate exposure. The founder left for Dubai following the allegations of fraud. Barclays held £600M of exposure; Elliott Management £200M. AlixPartners were appointed administrators.

**The common thread**

In all three cases, the borrower acted as its own servicer, controlled the collection accounts, and provided the data on which lenders relied to assess their own exposure. Facilities that appeared secured and self-liquidating on paper depended in practice on the integrity of the party under the greatest financial stress. Building genuine control infrastructure requires meaningful operational effort. Relying on trust where control is possible carries a cost that is now becoming very clear.

Sona's conclusion — "this was avoidable" — is confirmed by legal commentary following the MFS collapse. Independent collateral verification, origination exclusivity, and control of the servicing function were all available structural protections that were not taken, primarily because competitive pressures and deal velocity had led participants to move away from these practices during the expansion phase.

Jamie Dimon put it bluntly in February 2026: "I see a couple of people doing some dumb things in private credit markets." The "cockroach theory" — that one visible problem usually signals others hiding nearby — has become the unofficial framing for what comes next.

