## 6. The PE entanglement — why the two crises are one

Marks makes the most important structural connection that is often treated as background context: private credit and private equity are not parallel crises. They are the same crisis viewed from two sides of the capital structure.

PE was born and grew to scale during a 40-year, 2,000bp decline in interest rates. The specific mechanism: falling rates increase the value of future cash flows (making portfolio companies worth more) and reduce the cost of borrowing (reducing the interest burden on LBO debt). PE firms that bought companies using borrowed money received a double bonus from the rate decline. This was the structural tailwind that made the industry look better than it was.

When the Fed raised rates by 400bp between 2022 and 2023, Bruce Karsh's formulation was precise: "A lot of private equity companies have been saddled with capital structures that didn't anticipate a 400-basis point increase in interest rates." The consequences cascade mechanically:

Higher interest costs made many portfolio companies less profitable. Higher rates meant higher interest bills and lower coverage ratios, making it more difficult to refinance. Rising rates reduced the value to buyers of companies' future cash flows, lowering the prices at which portfolio companies can be sold. As sales slowed, distributions to PE LPs fell, making it harder for LPs to commit to new funds, further constraining the capital available for new investments.

The PE stress transmits directly to private credit through four specific channels. PE is the primary borrower in direct lending — approximately 75% of direct loans are to PE-backed companies. PE's inability to sell portfolio companies is the primary mechanism by which maturities cannot be repaid at face value. PE's declining willingness to support portfolio companies through equity injections — documented by Lincoln in 2025 — is the mechanism by which bilateral LME recovery rates deteriorate from 75% to something lower. And PE's fundraising difficulties reduce the future demand for direct lending capital, compressing the AUM growth trajectory that justifies alt manager equity valuations.

The MSCI PE return data Marks cites is stark: annualised returns of 5.8% versus 11.6% for the S&P 500 over 2022–Q3 2025. LP capital committed in expectation of the returns that justified the allocation is instead locked in vehicles that have underperformed public markets by 580bp per year for three years. This is the pressure that drives LP behaviour — redemption requests, reduced new commitments, rotation away from direct lending toward PE, infrastructure, and secondaries.

