## 7. The 1929 structural parallel

Marks draws a precise structural parallel between the conditions that created the Great Crash of 1929 and the conditions prevailing in direct lending today. Three elements were primarily responsible for the 1929 bubble:

**The sale of stock to the public without regard for suitability.** Individual investors were lured into a market whose risks they did not understand after an ascent that had gone on for years. The promoters were eager for commissions and not focused on suitability.

**The provision of heavy leverage to the buyers.** Margin loans for up to 90% of the purchase price were available. Leverage was touted as profit-enhancing; the downside risk was often omitted from the sales pitch.

**The mismatch between asset illiquidity and the short-term nature of the loans.** Margin debt could be called if a decline wiped out the equity cushion and additional cash couldn't be posted. The perhaps-unmentioned terms of margin debt exposed investors to the risk of ruin.

The direct lending parallel:

Individual investors placed in non-traded BDCs did not fully grasp the potential complications, especially since the instruments had never been tested in tough times. The inclusion of leverage in the vehicles — back leverage borrowed by the BDC against its loan portfolio — was described as capable of magnifying profits; the corresponding downside risk was often omitted from the sales pitch. And the investment vehicles' limitations on liquidity — which may have been glossed over with a representation that "most of the time, you'll probably be okay" — have come into play with surprising effect.

Marks's conclusion: it is not easy to lose everything in the stock market or in credit, but the combination of these three elements can do the trick in a bad-enough boom/bust cycle. The institutional question — whether the redemption gates will hold and whether the bilateral LME advantage will produce the 70–80% recovery rates MS projects — determines whether this is a contained cycle or something more serious.

