## 9. The manager incentive dilemma

Both sources address what is perhaps the most uncomfortable truth about the current situation: the managers who got into trouble were not necessarily negligent or dishonest. Many were responding rationally to the incentive environment they operated in.

Marks's framing is the clearest: "What a choice for a manager: join in when feverish investors are lowering their standards in order to put money to work, or sit on the sidelines and not invest, watching as other managers pile up AUM, and likely causing clients to close their accounts in the seemingly interminable period before your skepticism and discipline finally pay off?"

This is the structural explanation for why underwriting standards deteriorated across the industry, not just at one or two outlier managers. When the alternative to competing on price and terms is losing your client base, most managers compete. The ones who don't — Oaktree's AUM "only" doubled over the last decade versus 174% growth at the five largest managers — incur a real business cost during the expansion phase. The payoff for restraint comes during the correction, when better-priced opportunities emerge and capital flows toward managers with preserved reputations and conservative portfolios.

Sona adds the portfolio management dimension to this. The discipline that matters is not just origination standards but ongoing willingness to recognise and exit bad decisions. Public credit managers have this discipline by default because prices are continuous and visible — a deteriorating bond is immediately observable in the secondary market, and a manager who fails to sell it before recovery deteriorates is penalised in performance reports. Private credit managers have no equivalent mechanism. There is no secondary market. PIK amendments preserve the par mark. The incentive is always to delay recognition and hope for recovery.

The practical question for LP investors: which managers built portfolio management infrastructure commensurate with their origination capacity, and which built origination infrastructure and assumed monitoring could be largely mechanical? The answer to that question will determine returns over the next three to five years more than any macro variable.

