## 11. The historical rhyme: direct lending as HY 1989

Bob O'Leary, writing to Marks, makes the most useful forward-looking analogy in either document:

"It strikes me that there are interesting parallels between credit markets today and the late 1980s/early '90s, when you and Bruce started the first Special Credits funds. Back then, there was a new financial innovation (high yield bonds) that many investors had over-indulged in. The market suddenly got spooked by a war in the Middle East, and investors couldn't dump high yield fast enough. Substitute direct lending for high yield and add an element of technological creative destruction, and you have some of the same dynamics (including another war in the Middle East sparking fears of recession). Ultimately, high yield was fine (even great), and direct lending will be as well, but it may have to go through a credit cycle to get to a better place."

The HY parallel is instructive precisely because HY did survive and improve. The late 1980s saw the collapse of Drexel Burnham, a wave of LBO-related defaults, and widespread investor disillusionment with the junk bond market. Returns on HY had been genuinely strong in the early years and then eroded as capital flooded in and standards fell, exactly as Marks's bubble pattern predicts. The resolution was not the elimination of the asset class — it was a repricing, a shakeout of weaker managers, a tightening of underwriting standards, and ultimately the creation of a more mature, better-functioning market that has served investors well for 30+ years.

The three differences in the current situation that Sona highlights as potentially making this cycle harder than HY 1989: the retail capital in non-traded vehicles creates redemption dynamics that BSL and HY did not have; the 60% asset-light exposure means recovery values are structurally more uncertain; and the originate-not-manage culture, if it persists, means the cycle will expose more problems than a simple repricing would fix.

The three factors that make resolution more likely than catastrophe: capital is largely locked up and gates are functioning, preventing the fire-sale dynamics that created systemic contagion in 2008; banks are not the primary holders of the risk and their look-through LTV provides substantial structural protection; and the bilateral LME structure, for the well-managed portfolios at least, enables soft restructurings that preserve value rather than destroying it.

