## 12. What comes next — the resolution path

Both sources converge on a resolution path with common features, though they differ on timing and severity.

The near-term catalyst is the May 2026 Q1 BDC filings. These will be the first marks incorporating all three stresses simultaneously — the Iran-driven rate shock, AI disruption of software revenues, and Q1 2026 SaaS earnings. If PIK stays below 10% and ICR remains above 1.7×, the unverifiability premium that currently dominates BDC NAV discounts will compress rapidly. If marks deteriorate materially, the fundamental credit loss estimate grows. Either way, this is the information event that resolves the binary.

The medium-term dynamic is a repricing and consolidation. Sona: the market will emerge stronger once the excesses of past cycles have washed away. Dispersion in returns will reveal a great deal about the skill and credibility of private credit managers. Some will thrive, some will survive, and some will no longer be active. Marks: investor scepticism is likely to give rise to investment opportunities that are much better than those passed up in the period just ended. Staying disciplined and resisting the latest fads is not the route to short-term maximisation, but it is essential for the excellence in investing that the best managers seek.

The long-term structural shift, on which both are clear, is toward integrated public-private credit management. Sona's "if you don't do both, you should not do either" is the practitioner formulation. Marks's lifetime of moving between public and private credit through cycles — always insisting there was a place in portfolios for both — is the proof of concept. The managers who succeed in the next decade will be those with the ability to move across the full credit spectrum as dislocations emerge, using public market price discovery to stress-test private marks, and deploying in both markets as relative value dictates.

The winners are already identifiable: managers with low software and asset-light exposure, high institutional capital ratios, robust portfolio management infrastructure, cross-market origination capability, and distressed funds positioned to deploy in H2 2026–2028 as the software maturity wall forces cash settlements. The losers are already identifiable too: managers with high retail capital ratios, concentrated software exposures, origination-only cultures, and non-traded BDCs facing sustained redemption pressure.

The cycle will run. Direct lending will, as O'Leary and Marks believe, ultimately be fine — even great. But it will have to earn that outcome by going through a credit cycle that exposes the flaws that were overlooked during the years when everything was going well. That is not a counsel of despair. It is the eternal pattern.

